04153nam a22005415i 9780226753591DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021009504  a97802267535917 a10.7208/97802267535912doi  a(DE-B1597)589129  a(OCoLC)1251446821  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aN7483.M39bK58 2021 4aN7483 7aART0000002bisacsh04a709.041 aKitnick, Alex, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDistant Early Warning :bMarshall McLuhan and the Transformation of the Avant-Garde /cAlex Kitnick. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b56 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Age of Mechanical Production -- t2. What It Means to Be Avant-Garde -- t3. Lights On -- t4. Electronic Opera -- t5. Massage, ca. 1966 -- t6. Information Environment -- t7. Culture Was His Business -- tPostscript: McLuhan’s Art Today -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMarshall McLuhan (1911–1980) is best known as a media theorist—many consider him the founder of media studies—but he was also an important theorist of art. Though a near-household name for decades due to magazine interviews and TV specials, McLuhan remains an underappreciated yet fascinating figure in art history. His connections with the art of his own time were largely unexplored, until now. In Distant Early Warning, art historian Alex Kitnick delves into these rich connections and argues both that McLuhan was influenced by art and artists and, more surprisingly, that McLuhan’s work directly influenced the art and artists of his time. Kitnick builds the story of McLuhan’s entanglement with artists by carefully drawing out the connections among McLuhan, his theories, and the artists themselves. The story is packed with big names: Marcel Duchamp, Niki de Saint Phalle, Jasper Johns, Andy Warhol, Nam June Paik, and others. Kitnick masterfully weaves this history with McLuhan’s own words and his provocative ideas about what art is and what artists should do, revealing McLuhan’s influence on the avant-garde through the confluence of art and theory. The illuminating result sheds light on new aspects of McLuhan, showing him not just as a theorist, or an influencer, but as a richly multifaceted figure who, among his many other accolades, affected multiple generations of artists and their works. The book finishes with Kitnick overlaying McLuhan’s ethos onto the state of contemporary and post-internet art. This final channeling of McLuhan is a swift and beautiful analysis, with a personal touch, of art’s recent transgressions and what its future may hold.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aArt criticismxHistoryy20th century. 0aArt, Moderny20th centuryxPhilosophy. 0aAvant-garde (Aesthetics) 0aAvant-garde (Aesthetics). 7aART / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073919040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226753591423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226753591/original  a978-3-11-073919-0  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles